<subSubSection id="57944B91534D3463F3B2A5491B87E000" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="72AA2A015008E5CF959C1005523DB830" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Berlese described this american form as a variety of 
<taxonomicName id="6906933BDBB2FE9A6F9E4EADDCE77A54" class="Arachnida" family="Brachychthoniidae" genus="Brachychthonius" genus.bestMatchDistance="52" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">B. brevis Berlese</taxonomicName>
(non Michael). I studied slide no 83/10 from Lake City, Florida, which probably is the type. This specimen is only slightly different from 
<taxonomicName id="87F22FDD273FD177AED26407167A7E59" class="Arachnida" family="Brachychthoniidae" genus="Brachychthonius" genus.bestMatchDistance="93" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="italicus">B. italicus</taxonomicName>
and I agree with Jacot that it must be considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="A718409D1647CB731E05F44B3F2B6911" class="Arachnida" family="Brachychthoniidae" genus="Brachychthonius" genus.bestMatchDistance="109" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="italicus">B. italicus</taxonomicName>
; Forsslund (in litt.) kindly informed me that he is of the same opinion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
